  address = {New York},
  urldate = {2009-06-01},
  abstract = {It is a mistake to ignore or minimize the social significance of public behavior in common everyday situations suggests Goffman and anyone even remotely familiar with the professor's previous works on the subject (Encounters, 1961; Behavior in Public Places, 1963; Interaction Ritual, 1967) will have a good idea of the thrust of the six sequentially related essays here. Observance of the ceremonial ...  More ground rules which govern routine face-to-face interaction (waiting in line, walking down the street, riding in an elevator, dining out) not only reveals much about individual self-images and attitudes toward others but also forms an extremely powerful, albeit hidden, guilt-based social control mechanism; failure to observe normative behavior, on the other hand, generates interpersonal discomfort and distrust and, unless corrective interchanges are initiated, the offender is usually punished so as to maintain ""public"" (i.e., interpersonal) order. Sometimes however punishment is self-inflicted, characterized by loss of confidence, onset of mental problems, etc. Specifically, these essays, which build on Goffman's prior studies and contain some redundancy, analyze individual territorial preserves (situational and egocentric rather than spatial), supportive and remedial interchanges, tie-signs, and ""normal appearances"" as criminal disguise; a seventh essay, ""The Insanity of Place,"" is appended, meant to be applied to the theories developed in the other pieces. Goffman, who teaches sociology and anthropology at the University of Pennsylvania, is ultimately concerned with the increasing, incivility and social breakdown found in American urban life and this book adds another impressive building block to his unique, acute examination of the small behaviors which contribute to that phenomenon.},
  keywords = {performance,public,social behavior,social relations,sociology}
}

